#Text=Obama commutes whistleblower 's sentence :
#Text=Chelsea Manning to walk free in 120 days
#Text=Wednesday , January 18 , 2017
#Text=Yesterday , mere days before he is to leave office , U.S. President Barack Obama commuted the sentence of Army intelligence officer Chelsea Manning from 35 years to time served .

#Text=Manning , who in 2010 released thousands of classified documents to the public through WikiLeaks detailing abuses of the Iraq and Afghanistan wars , has already served almost seven years in prison and is now scheduled for release on May 17 of this year
#Text=Artist 's rendition of Manning as she views herself .
#Text=Image : Alicia Neal .

#Text=The information Manning released to the public through WikiLeaks and The Guardian in 2010 included diplomatic accounts , videos , military incident logs , and battle plans , including footage of an American Apache helicopter firing on suspected Iraqi insurgents , reports of prisoners held in Guantanamo Bay without trial , and records of detainees abused by the Iraqi military .
#Text=Many in Congress have denounced Manning as a traitor , stating the breach endangered U.S. national security .
#Text=Manning was convicted in 2013 of 22 charges , including espionage , but acquitted of aiding the enemy .

#Text=Republican senator John McCain , who ran for president against Obama in 2008 , said " It is a sad , yet perhaps fitting commentary on President Obama 's failed national security policies that he would commute the sentence of an individual that endangered the lives of American troops , diplomats , and intelligence sources by leaking hundreds of thousands of sensitive government documents to WikiLeaks , a virulently anti-American organization that was a tool of Russia 's recent interference in our elections . "

column1: #Text=Not everyone has considered Manning 's actions to be wrong .
#Text=" Chelsea Manning exposed serious abuses , " says Margaret Huang , executive director of the U.S. branch of Amnesty International , " and as a result her own human rights have been violated . "
#Text=Huang went on to call Obama 's order for Manning 's release " long overdue . "
#Text=Despite being a trans woman , Manning was housed in a men 's prison , the U.S. Disciplinary Barracks at Fort Leavenworth , Kansas .
#Text=She spent a long period in solitary confinement and attempted suicide twice in 2016 .
#Text=Obama 's staff told the press
#Text=WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange 's promise to agree to U.S. extradition if Manning was granted clemency had nothing to do with the decision .
#Text=Assange is currently living in the Ecuadorian embassy in London , where he is claiming asylum .
#Text=He faces rape accusations from two Swedish women .
#Text=The Obama administration has seen what The New York Times calls an " unprecedented crackdown on leaks of government secrets . "
#Text=Manning is among more than 1,500 individuals whom President Obama has granted clemency during his tenure .
#Text=White House Press Secretary Josh Ernest was asked if NSA whistleblower Edward Snowden would also be pardoned .

#Text=Ernest said no , saying the information Snowden released was more dangerous to the U.S. public and pointed out that while Manning had gone through a formal trial and acknowledged wrongdoing , " Mr. Snowden fled into the arms of an adversary and has sought refuge in a country that most recently made a concerted effort to undermine confidence in our democracy . "

#Text=This week , Obama also commuted the sentences of Oscar Lopez Rivera , a Puerto Rican nationalist linked to bombings in the 1970s and 1980s , James E. Cartwright , a former Marine general and White House Chief of Staff convicted of lying to the FBI , and over two hundred other individuals , mostly drug offenders .
#Text=He also pardoned 63 people outright .
